The cruder measure of U.S. life expectancy continues to rise, but with some deceleration [[http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/278758/end-future-peter-thiel?page=2|The End of the Future - Peter Thiel - National Review Online]]
----
The monetary system is crutch, as is the pharmaceutically-centered medical industry. The quality of food is declining, which has a direct effect on cognition. Aspartame and MSG, laden in junk foods, are excitotoxins. Moreover, the US media cultivates a paradigm of ignorance, distraction, and desensitization. US imperialism continues to divert resources toward killing Middle Eastern civilians. These glitches all retard what we would think of as progress. 


The internet has expanded the human capacity for knowledge acquisition and long-distance communication. It is like a thousand libraries of Alexandria, accessible to (eventually) anyone. The potential for scientific advancement is immense, and we are seeing it everywhere. A problem is that the status quo suppresses the truly groundbreaking revelations. This is changing, the power structure is in contempt, as evidenced by the massive, global civil unrest.


I would disagree with Thiel. While an excellent commentary, "progress" does not move linearly. Kuhn described a dynamic of punctuated equilibrium, defined by periodic paradigm shifts. Economically, the Western markets are in state of melancholy, suspended animation, and, as of today, have an elevated probability of catastrophic failure. This is Schumpeter's process of creative destruction at work: before a new, more efficient system can arise, the rotten core must be discarded and rebuilt anew. [[https://mail.google.com/mail/u/0/#inbox/132dc25ab457582b|Gmail - The End of the Future - cognitionmachine@gmail.com]]
